{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639066"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17758"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72247"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10472"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24447"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72247"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being involved in a car crash. He is agitated and has multiple facial bruises, swollen eyes, and lacerations on his scalp. There is clear liquid coming from his nose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the clear liquid coming from the nose?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea","Allergic rhinitis","Nasal mucosal injury","Tear duct injury","Sinus infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clear liquid coming from the nose in the context of recent head trauma is most likely due to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when there is a fracture at the base of the skull, leading to a leak of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) into the nasal cavity. The presence of CSF rhinorrhea is a serious finding as it indicates a breach in the protective barrier of the brain, increasing the risk of meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic rhinitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes clear nasal discharge, but it is unlikely in this context of acute trauma and other significant injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal mucosal injury\u003C/strong\u003E could cause bleeding or discharge, but the clear nature of the fluid and the traumatic context suggest CSF rather than simple mucosal injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETear duct injury\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically cause clear nasal discharge, especially in the context of head trauma. It would more likely result in tearing or blood-stained tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinus infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause nasal discharge, but it is usually not clear and would not be the immediate consideration following trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clear nasal discharge following head trauma may indicate cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea, suggesting a skull base fracture.","CSF rhinorrhea is a serious condition that requires prompt evaluation and management to prevent complications such as meningitis.","Facial trauma with signs of skull base fracture necessitates careful neurological assessment and imaging."],"references":["Mathias T, Levy J, Fatakia A, McCoul ED. Contemporary Approach to the Diagnosis and Management of Cerebrospinal Fluid Rhinorrhea. Ochsner J. 2016 Summer;16(2):136-42. PMID: 27303222; PMCID: PMC4896656.","Keshri A, Jain R, Manogaran RS, Behari S, Khatri D, Mathialagan A. Management of Spontaneous CSF Rhinorrhea: An Institutional Experience. J Neurol Surg B Skull Base. 2019 Oct;80(5):493-499. doi: 10.1055/s-0038-1676334. Epub 2018 Dec 5. PMID: 31534891; PMCID: PMC6748837.","Tohge R, Takahashi M. Cerebrospinal Fluid Rhinorrhea and Subsequent Bacterial Meningitis due to an Atypical Clival Fracture. Intern Med. 2017;56(14):1911-1914. doi: 10.2169/internalmedicine.56.8186. Epub 2017 Jul 15. PMID: 28717092; PMCID: PMC5548689.","Zhang F, Zeng T, Gao L, Cui DM, Wang K, Xu ZJ, Cao XY. Treatment of traumatic cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea via extended extradural anterior skull base approach. Chin J Traumatol. 2021 Sep;24(5):280-285. doi: 10.1016/j.cjtee.2021.06.002. Epub 2021 Jun 6. PMID: 34272118; PMCID: PMC8563860."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T05:55:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T05:57:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10472"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72247"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic